This was a random challenge and my opponents rating was very close to mine. I have annotated it in the hope that more skilful players can suggest more efficient ways that it could have come to a conclusion

As I don't remember seeing 2. Bf4 ever before I decided to open cautiously and play a reactive game until the position established itself.
Alternatives were Bd7 to recapture with the Bishop or letting it be and developing Nf6.  While the text lets off pressure on White's QP it gives a tempo as the Bishop can be chased.
Clearly to prevent 6. ... Bb4+ but in fact merely wastes a move.
This move is unclear to me.  Black's Queen's Bishop is undeveloped and in fact blocked behind the King's pawn and White needs the time to develop elsewhere.
Another speculative piece of aggression.
Offering the Bishop.  In almost any event due to White's lack of development Black gets a dominant center and pressure on White's Queen's pawn.
Preparing for e5 and probable exchange to follow.
Probably not the best because it commits the Bishop to defence of the side pawn.  However circumscribing White's bishop seems worthwhile.
Moment of truth.  White's best option is likely 17. c4 to counter even if it loses the pawn eventually.
A speculative line.  If White defends correctly it's a bit of a waste but on 20. ... c5 the Queen has a retreat.
Black is up two pawns: White is in a bind as he ought to keep the Rook but cannot give control of the only open file to Black.  His only advantage now is the two Bishops which are insufficient.

Opposite color Bishops make for a draw but not when Black is up two pawns and two are passed!  White needed to avoid the piece exchange instead of seeking it out.

Black's play to finish is I think imprecise but gets the job done eventually.
45. ... g4 is better to avoid disconnecting the pawns.
63. ... Qxh3 probably finishes faster.
Checkmate.
The French. Pretty boring for a blitz game so I try to sharpen the position a bit.
Now either the Rubinstein variation or Winawer leads to a more sharp position.
!? The exclamation mark being only for the audacity of playing the BDG. Still in a blitz game it is a pretty fierce weapon.

?! A bit ambitious by Black although nothing horrible right away. Just doesn't seem "right". Black should not be focusing on activity but rather developing safely and protecting his pawn advantage. 

6. Be7 seems safer.

? I knew this move was a mistake the second I saw it without having to calculate any variations or see any tactics. Black should not castle this early against a gambit such as the BGD and with all of white's pieces aimed at the kingside Black just seems wrong.  

better is 7. Nbd7
Black gains some sense and moves his bishop back to e7 but ultimately wastes a tempo in his b4 to e7 excursion.
Eyes the bishop on e7 and the h4 square. Black needs to tread very carefully.
Blocking the h7 diagonal but at a cost. Black's position now looks gross. With all the weak darksquares around the kingside white should have a strong attack.

! Black cannot take the knight due to 11 Bxe7 forking the queen and rook and white retains the attack. 

Also brings in another attacker.
A logical move trying to get rid of the pesky pin.
White grabs control of even more dark squares.
? This just loses straight away. Although Black was in a poor position as white is threatening to evict the d5 knight and proceed with the attack.
! Removes the h7 defender. The rest is just cleanup

Black was probably prepared for a slow quiet french when he walked into the BGD. With one of two dubious moves he quickly fell behind in development and castled into the classic white kingside attack using all the white pieces except the a1 rook. 

Was quite simple and cute but still the flow and ease of the attack made me want to annotate the game.

In stead of answering with a central pawn like e5 or d5 black plays c5 attacking the d square and preventing white to play d4 instantly. Off course playing 2.d4 is still possible but if I were white I would follow it up with a pawn sacrifice by playing c3. This ends up in: 1.e4-c5 2.d4-cxd4 3.c3. Black can now accept the sacrifice but I never do because white creates a lot more space on his queens side. It's not a disadvantage but I prefer a more enclosed type of game and I'd rather not give away too much space from the start.
As for 3.Qxd4 it's just a bad move. You do not want to expose your queen too early in the game and certainly not when the other player can develop while attacking it.
My personal favourite however 2....-Nc6 or e6 are possible as well.
The most played move by white resulting in the Open Sicilian.
You can off course decline taking the pawn and follow up with 3....-Nf6. But you'll end up capturing it in the next move anyway so just capture it at this moment.

Najdorf variation. My personal favourite.
The idea behind a6 is that black wants to play e5 eventually to chase the white knight off the d4 square and gaining position in the centre. However playing it instantly without a6 is not a good idea. White can play:
5....-e5 6.Bb5-Nbd7 7. Nf5-a6 8.Bxd7-Qxd7. With 6....-Bb7 the outcome is the same. White has a much stronger position at this point. A lot of space first of all and pieces that develop easily. In fact white only needs to castle and develop Bc1. Whereas black still needs to make space to develop his bishops. Still it's being played and I believe it's even a variation but I don't know the name. I wouldn't recommend it though.
By playing 5...-a6 black prevents in fact any piece from taking position at b5. Which is positive because Sicilian often ends up in a race between white and black. White attacking the kings side. Black attacking the queens side. 5...-a6 prepares that attack for black

Number of choices for white here:
6.Be3 is usually followed by e5. This is the main line and the easiest for white since he only needs to get the queen out of the way to d2 to castle on the queens side. Off course he will first need to move the knight from d4 to a more passive square. The attack for white continues then by playing f3 followed by g4. I believe that when you don't play the Dragon Sicilian you shouldn't be to afraid of the pawn storm by white on the kings side.
6. Bg5 or Bc4 is followed by e6. The only reason I can think of is that both moves gain a certain control over d5. Bc4 directly and Bg5 by pinning the knight.
You don't want that square to be weak in the first opening moves. So you play e6

White feels b5 coming and moves his bishop out of the way. A common played move at this point. The bischop also remains it's aim at the kings side for a later attack.
Trying to prevent b5 by playing a4 is not a good option I'd say.
It would result in: 7.a4-Nxe4 8.Nxe4-d5 9.bxd5-Qxd5. White has now 2 knights in the centre but no pawns and those knights can be easily chased by playing f5 somewhere down the line.
Black also has an incredible amount of space to move around.

b5 is also possible at this point.
But white is going to play f4 and Qf3. So you want to have played b5 and your knight to c5 by then. 
White's idea is to push the pawn on the f-line further up the board. You want to be ahead of him with your pawn on the b-line. Playing Nc5 also keeps pressure on whites pawn on e4.

Standard play. I wouldn't play f3 to be followed up by g4 because you're going to be late.
Black will push more pieces out like Nc5 and also move up the pawn on the b-line.
Blacks pawn is obviously more threatening so the knight needs to get out of the way.

By playing Na4 I'm obliged to square the bishop. However I was going to anyway since I would like to play e5 further down the line and I'd rather be rid of this bishop aimed at my kings side and the unprotected d5 square.

Again moving my pawn in a better position while attacking one of his pieces. He looses a tempo while I gain one by developing a piece. Remember I'm far behind due to the pawn play in the beginning of the opening.
Whites pawn on e4 also becomes weak and as for my weaker pawn on d6: it is not under any attack at the moment and can be easily defended.
The f5 move has opened up an extra line for an attack on my kings side. So I decided to postpone going for the castle.

Developing a piece and attacking the e4 square at the same time.
Sometimes chess does not have to be difficult. Develop your pieces into a strong position and make your opponent loose tempos by keeping the pressure on his weaker points.
If you don't see the attack immediately position your pieces on easy defensible squares and wait for the him/her to create the opening. Off course this is situation dependent. If you wait too long your opponent has an advantage in the end game

again attacking an undefended point.
According to the computer analysis I should have played:
14.Ng3-Nxe4 if white accepts the sacrifice: 15. Nxe4-Qh4+ 16.Kf1-Qxe4 gaining a pawn.

Prevents c5 and more importantly prevents cxb4.
If played it will be followed up by Bxb4+ gaining another tempo

White starts to think about defending rather than attacking. Usually a good sign.
Although I think white could have played this stronger.

Nevertheless. Black has a lot of advantages. Open c en d lines for the rooks. A bishop on the dark squares that can easily move around and attack the kings side. A pawn on the e line that isn't blocked by an opposing pawn.
White doesn't immediately have an attack.
Moving my knight to a centre square and adding more pressure to the attack on c3 plus defending the pawn on b4
Qe4 would have been better.

Should have played Qc6.
But I was too excited about gaining the advantage that I might as well trade of the queens and head off into the mid game.

Bxc3 would have been better. White does loose the bishop in exchange for a knight but with the pawn on c3 whites bishop no longer has a line to the right side of the board (from blacks perspective)
Opens up the b-line as well for my rooks further down the line.

Bad move. I was afraid of castling and loosing the pawn on e5 but if I would have given this a little more thougt I would have spotted:
23. Kf2-0-0 24. Nd7-Rfe8. 25. Nxe5-Bh4+ 26. g3- Rxe5

Black finds himself in a position where he has blocked himself somewhat with his king and pieces around it. And with white moving up his pawns on the board he will soon be in a position to attack again.

The idea is to start up an attack by use of the open b-line.
White can play a rook to b1 for the exchange but black will come out stronger:
26. Rhb1-Rxb1 27.Rxb1-Bd3 28.Re1- Rb8 29.Bc1
White can now only think about defending and black has an entire open a-line for the pawn to advance.
According to me white is stalling here. Trying to get all his pieces out of the way of the Rook on b2.
attacking the only piece defending Bd2

So white moves it out of the way. Where he should have put pressure on Nd5 by playing Ra5.
White never prevented me from doubling my rooks on the b-line. 
And by moving the bishop to e1 I don't even need Rab8.
Putting pressure on Ne4 which has to move since it can no longer be defended. This allows me to play e4+

White has opened up quite some lines for me to move around and get my pieces out of their passive position.
His king is forced onto the h-line.

I should have played g6 here but I was hoping he didn't see the mate that was coming and I got lucky. 
When playing g6 you are actually preparing a mate by playing Ne3 followed by Ng2.
And there isn't much white can do about that. Except giving away more quality.
Possibilities are to play 32. Nb7-Be5 33.Nd8-Rxd8 34. Nxd8-Kg7 35. Bg3 (or else mate in 2 by playing g5 followed by forced Kh5 and Nf4)- g5 36. Kh5-Bxg3
It's not a done deal yet but black controls the e1 square to promote his pawn. 
Also whites rooks aren't contributing much to the game. And black can easily clean up the pawn on c3 which gives him even more advantage.
Obviously white also still needs to be careful of not being mated by Nf4.

White didn't see the mate coming.
Rh8 can only be delayed not prevented.

It may be scary to play a game of chess with someone who is significantly higher rated than you but there are some advantages to it as well. Firstly you can only improve your game to the level of your competition. Secondly a higher rated play can provide valuable feedback about your game and areas of need improvement. 

I usually play 1.d4 but when faced against a lower rated player I play 1.e4 which is more familiar to them.
most common is 2. Nf3 moving into Spanish games

?! this is inferior to 2. ...Nf6 because it hinders piece development. The general rule to keep in mind when playing through the opening is to develop knight before bishops bishops before queen and Queen before rooks. If you follow this rule you will have a good position coming out of the opening 80% of the time.

Normally I would only recommend this move only after the majority of your pieces have been developed. However this is an exception because 2. ...c6 has left ...e5 undefended. If black decides to capture with 3. ...exf4. Then white recaptures with e3 and Bxf4 to follow. 

Strategically speaking 3. ....exf4 is very good for white because it weakens black's center by deflecting the e pawn away from the center while white's center pawns remain in the center. It also will give white the plus of rapid deployment of his pieces.

?? putting your bishop in front of a unmoved center pawn is never a good move. This move hems in black's queen LSB and Knight. Alternative suggestions to defend the pawn would be ...d6 to keep the center semi closed or go for broke with ...exf4
...d6 would have prevented me from capturing ...e5 right way. Had black played 3. ...d6 I would have followed up with Nf3.
retreating the bishop to c7 or e7 was safer. Now I can setup a very powerful center.
?? I am sure he was thinking "If he takes with the knight I take back with the pawn." but...
!! For the win. I win a pawn.
a good pin
developing a piece and preparing for castling.
?? never move this pawn unless your forced because of a check on h7.
and this why playing ...h6 is almost always bad
The cannon is all lined up and ready to destroy
mate in two.
Still best by test even today.
The gambit must be accepted!

Pressing onward.

Continuing to press the attack.
Keeping the White Queen away from the action.
Moving a defender out of the way.
Closing in.
With dangerous promotion threats.
Forcing White's response.
With mate to follow. McDonnell resigns here.

Hi everyone!

Sadly I have to report on a second loss in my MT against the masters.  This is also the second time that I have castled kingside and my opponent has mounted a successful mating attack.  This attack did not result in me copping Old Matey but I lost ruinous amounts of material which was sufficient grounds for me to wave the white flag.  How did this happen?  Well gameknot analysis is provided here: http://gameknot.com/analyze-board.pl?bd=15890363&fb=1&rnd=0.3149043367856525.
2. ...... d5 - we both play a double d pawn opening and Dongoodman follows up with the Mason Opening 2. Bf4.
5. Ngf3 - both sides develop their pieces rapidly.
7. ..... Rb8 - this move is forced to defend my b7 pawn.
8. ..... 0-0 - In retrospect I wonder if I was now castling into it (yet again!).  Was Bxf4 an improvement?

11. ..... Bxg3?! - apparently GK analysis did not like this move.  I think it is 'cos it opens up the h column.   Henry is certainly gonna need that pair of medieval stockings from Glenda plus 5 extra wolf pelts plus some p(r)awn vindaloo in order to keep warm in that draughty castle of his!
13. ..... Ne7 - Glenda's steed comes over to the kingside to help in the defense of Henry.
15. ..... Bg6 - trying to keep the position as closed as possible so Fou Leblanc challenges Dongoodman's lsb on the b1-h7 diagonal.
17. 0-0-0 - castling on the opposite side and preparing a line up of rooks on the h column perhaps?

19. Qxd3 - the exchange of lsbs was to try and relieve some of the pressure around Henry.  I thought I had things well in control here particularly as I have a rook controlling the h column.  I just wish I could swap Glenda and my b8 rook around though then I could have got an attack going down the h column onto white's doubletons on the g column.  Alas I only realised two moves later that it is the F COLUMN that is under the hammer and white exploits this very well.

19. ..... Rh6 - this move is meant to be versatile to prepare a future doubling of rooks on the g column and to also defend my knight on f6 which is pinned to my f7 pawn.  Yup the f7 square is certainly gonna be my achillees heel here.  My next move c6 which turned out to be an outright blunder was to prepare such a move as Qc7 followed by Rh8.  But white side-tracked me with 21. Qe3.

21. Qe3 - which puts my g5 pawn under the hammer and thanks to that pesky white knight on e5 I cannot play Rg6 to defend it.  Hmm was Rh5 a better try than my plausible but erroneous next move?  You the Inquest Jury decide!
22. Qxg5+ - sssss and double sssss here comes the Wicked Witch to devastating effect.
22. ..... Kf8 - forced as either alternative king move to h8 or h7 will result in a nasty knight fork on f7.

25. Ng6+ - Ouch and double ouch!  A devastating knight fork/discovery combo on Henry Glenda and my rook on b8 now results in ruinous loss of material.  I waved the white flag after white swiped my rook.  Coach Ion is quite correct I still need to brush up on my tactics in order to hold my own against The Titans and to retain Class A status.  The only thing I can say is that I fell into the tactical shot under extreme pressure.  I just hope I can redeem myself a little with the white pieces in my return challenge against Dongoodman.  I hope you have a good read and a nice evening.  Bye for now - Joanne

This game features a new signing for the England team redka aka Anna against a lady from IHS team ITALIA in a little mini-international. White starts off conventionally enough
And black replies with d5 the Centre Counter defence
White takes probably the best move.
And black re-captures the most usual move although Nf6 is perfectly playable.
This move is odd. White should be developing the minor pieces bishops and knights. Nc3 attacking the Qd5 is the most logical. This wastes a move and also blocks in the Bf1.
For some strange reason the Gameknot post-match computer database gives this as a mistake but I think it is a sound opening move. It grabs central control and opens up a diagonal for the Bf8.
An excellent move even better if played the move earlier.

I'm not happy with this retreat. Qa5 or Qd8 are the normal squares the queen moves to in this variation and I am sure that they are the best moves here too. Gameknot computer doesn't criticize it though!
Another excellent move by our heroine! White is developing and making threats - the best way to develop. Two pieces now attack the Pe5.
So black defends it again but Nc6 is better because now white has d4
Which she correctly plays. Black is already on the back foot. White has 2 pieces on e4 so black can't play e4. Black can't play Nc6 because white replies with d5.
This weakens the black king side doesn't help development. I think Nd7 or Pxd4 were better moves although the Gameknot computer doesn't criticize this move.
Not bad gaining space and attacking the black queen but I quite like the look of Pxe5 or the immediate g3 too.
Wrong square in my view the queen can just be attacked again.
Which white correctly does so!
The only safe square for the queen.
Preparing to develop the bishop to g2

I don't like this move as I think black needs to develop her other pieces she can't really afford to move a piece which has already moved once again. Ne7 and 0-0 screams out to me. Gameknot computer doesn't criticize this move (or any of the others since 5...Bd6) but I don't like it!

I think this is best. The Gameknot computer prefers Bd2 to prevent the doubling of the white c pawns but I don't think this is too much to worry about. The position is reasonably open so the bishops are probably worth slightly more than the knights. The white centre would be stronger by the exchange and white would have the semi-open b file for a rook.

This would be my first choice of move. GK computer prefers g5 which to me is not a developing move and weakens the black king side terribly. I'm coming to the conclusion that the GK computer is very weak! Do you agree dear reader?

I'm not convinced by this move. White just ignores the extra attack on the d5 pawn. The smart way to meet it would be 11. O-O Bxc3 
12. bxc3 Nxd5 13. Qh5+ g6 14. Qf3 and white wins back the pawn with advantage.

According to Irving Chernev here is what happened: "At this point Tarrasch played 5 P-K3. Alapin hardly looked at the board as he expected 5 P-K4 the customary move at the time. Almost automatically he touched his King Bishop as he intended to answer 5 P-K4 with 5... B-K2. Imagine his horror when he saw that his King Knight was attacked and he could not move it! He had touched his Bishop and regardless of the consequences he had to move his Bishop!" 

Alapin resigned at once. To play out the game a whole piece down against a master as great as Tarrasch would be hopeless.

The Rice Gambit. All games in this mini-tournament start from this position. It may not be a sound gambit by Grandmaster standards -- you won't see Anand break it out playing against Kramnik -- but one thing can be said for sure: it does lead to interesting play.
This game was one in which momentum shifted back and forth with almost every move. I momentarily equalize the material...
...only to blunder away the Exchange with this move...
...after my opponent comes up with this nice bit of tactical play.
I ended up getting a Pawn for the Exchange and a threatening one at that. My position isn't great but it's playable.
Time to start developing the Q-side.
With a Knight a Queen and two advanced Pawns pointing at my King's position my opponent has something going here. Time to focus on defense for me.

Momentarily freezing the Black Q to the K-file. With 17... QxQ 18 RxQ ch K-B3 Black could have entered an end game one Pawn up but he understandably thinks he can still attack my King which is isolated in the corner.
I decide to remove the threat by exchanging Queens.
Material is even again and with 20...K-B3 Black could have preserved the balance with a good chance of an eventual draw. The Knight would be unpinned and would threaten to capture my advanced Pawn.
A mistake. With the Knight still pinned now by the Bishop I can attack and win it with my QP.
Not only winning the Knight but if 23... K-B2 threatening 24 P-K6 dis ch with two connected advanced passed Pawns.
This however is worse. Now I can win the Rook on QR1 with a skewer.
Black's position looks hopeless but now it's my turn to blunder. I simply overlook 26... RxB.
The decisive blow. Now the Knight either must move or be captured allowing my Pawn to promote.
I still have to be slightly careful. With my King stuck on KN1 a back-rank mate possibility exists.
With the Rook -- and back-rank mate chance -- gone Black resigns.
To prevent b4 and White is forced to what seems an awkward Knight retreat.  Our database seems to suggest that castling is fine and the text clearly wastes time.
Assault on the King's pawn.  White's position is already a little off.
Looking for some counter-play.  If Black is drawn into 11. ... e5 then White can reestablish himself with 12. Nd5.
Cuts off the Bishop's attack on the King's pawn which had been preventing the massacre that follows.  I am unsure what Black's better option was.

White gets a little over-eager.  15. Nxe5 and Black must trade Queens (leaving White in control on the Queen's file no less) or retreat and White has his tempo back with the gain of a piece for a pawn.  The text leads to chaos.

White in the final reckoning traded a minor piece for two pawns.  He has moderately better development but his Queen looks vulnerable and his pawn structure is non-existent.  His only chance is to push the Queen-side (where he has a pawn majority by some miracle) hard and fast but the Knight is in the way.
Retreating the bishop was in order because of the placement of White's King and Rook.
Just as planned! - except White overlooked the incoming fork.

White resigns.

A messy game all around.  While I made significant mistakes (not least entering the final combination instead of retreating) it was a fairly even game.

The Giuoco Piano is my current major subject of chess study.  I have been playing on FICS recently and in games so far I have noticed that most players diverge (if White) after 4. ... Nf6 or (if Black) after 5. d4.  The resulting games vary wildly.

Here I play Black.  My opponent after the initial moves elects to exchange off as quickly as possible.  My goal in the game is to use this to my own advantage by dictating the timings and concentrating towards the center.
White plays to pick up a pawn quickly.

The normal 5. ... d5 is out.  On 6. exd5 6. ... Nb5 7. Qa4 Nxc4 8. Qxc4 Bd6 has Black into full retreat with the loss of a pawn - and that's the best option.  The text covers White's planned intrusion and develops the Rook.
White persists in the attack.  6. O-O and development or 6. d4 in the center would be preferable.  The result is going to be poor largely because of the Queen's over-ambition.

The exchange is a disaster for White even though the count comes even.  Black is developed and controls the center: White is entirely not and all his pieces are block in.

My game plan from here is to control the center gain a pawn majority as the position permits and roll to victory.
An uncalled for retreat.  The direct 10. ... d6 was in order.  d5 is playable as well although the result is an isolated King's pawn.
Retreat is not plausible and the fiancetto'd Bishop will attack e4.

If 12. Bxc5 bxc5 the Knights and pawns control the middle still and White loses his only developed piece - again.  The text aims to force a retreat but it's too early for White to resume his offensive as he gives away a pawn.  12. Nd2 was in order.  (Black follows with Bc7 or possibly Ng4.  If 12. ... Bxe3 13. fxe3 gives White a substantial center which will frustrate Black's control and threaten the Knight and King with O-O later.)
For now White has a substantial-looking center and Black pays the price for over-caution earlier.
And the direct assault does not help.  Better was d6 or possibly even Nc6.
White makes the most of his King-side majority.
This plays into White's attack and Rook advantage.  23. ... Nd7 was better.  Then if 24. b5 c5 and Black's position is better than the text.
24. b5 a5 was better since it ties down Black's two pieces.

Until this point White's attack had done well enough but the pressure is off now and Black's Knight is home free.  27. Kg3 was better and might have won the game for White.

Black is now looking to trade down.  With the pawn line strongly held the advantage of an extra piece should force at least a draw - even with a poorly placed bishop and no rook.
Gives away any remaining advantage to the ensuing Knight fork.  The correct move is Kh1.
White resigns.

When I first played the Gruenfeld this was regarded as a blunder as it allowed black to pin the knight with Bc8-g4. Instead Bc4 followed by Ne2 was recommended. I studied many games with this variation (for instance Boris Spassky beat Bobby Fischer with it at the Siegen Olympiad) and I have played it as black frequently. However in the 1980s this move came back into fashion combined with the pawn sacrifice which occours in the game.

Here is an example of a chess game where I easily could have won but I just messed around thinking the game would be easy and resulted in getting checkmated.
Up till now it was quite a usual beginning game.
My opponent did a move that many people do but I wouldn't do myself.
I obviously retreated my bishop.
The game now began to get more complicated.
Oooh my opponent made a tactical mistake as a bishop and a knight is stronger than a rook and a pawn- but that can be argued.
For a while nothing interesting happened in the game.
Now I had total control of the centre.
It was my opponent's turn to be attackive.
I fell for his trick.
I noticed this just as I submitted my move but by then it was too late.
I did my normal opening.
He probably did his normal opening.
I decided to attack his pawn.
He obviously protected it.
I took my bishop out hoping to put it in a good posistion.
He moved his pawn one forward probably guessing that I would bring my knight further up the board.
I castled to be on the safe side.
He planned to get his bishop out by moving his pawn forward.
I brung my other knight out.
He protected his knight with his bishop maybe thinking that I would move my bishop to b5.
I attacked his knight.
He attacked my bishop.
I didn't do much about that.
He took my pawn.
I took his pawn with my knight.
He took my bishop.
I took his knight.
He took my knight.
I didn't really have much choice and now I was controling the centre.
He attacked my knight because it was in a strong position.
I did a quite random move.
Suprisingly he did not take my knight.
I just completely missed taking his queen. I so should have won this game.
The game just carried on until he won but I soooooo should have won this game.
